sql:
SELECT COUNT(DISTINCT p.employee_id) AS number_of_promoted_employees
FROM promotions p
WHERE p.promotion_date >= DATE('now', '-1 year');

SELECT employees.employee_name, salaries.salary_level
FROM employees
INNER JOIN salaries ON employees.salary_id = salaries.salary_id;

external_knowledge:
- "happier workers" implies a satisfaction level above the departmental average;
- "taking on more projects" means having a higher number of projects than the departmental average;
- "more than 70% of the staff are sticking around" implies a retention rate greater than 70%.

- "Sailing smoothly" metaphorically refers to departments where employees are satisfied;
- "Active crew members" refers to employees with an 'active' status;
- "Mostly content" implies a satisfaction level above 0.5;
- "How many seamen are on board" refers to the count of active employees in each department;
- "Promotions granted" refers to the number of promotion records for employees in each department.

- "sail in the deep seas" metaphor for working in a department;
- "bustling crew" refers to departments with over ten employees;
- "ship's crew exceeds ten seafarers" means there are more than ten employees in a department;
- "names echo more than once in the maritime logs" indicates that an employee's name appears more than once in the records;
